description:
Follow-up to solov2-6ip. Today an operator can tell cold scan is running by tailing ~/.veska/logs/daemon.log for 'cold scan: starting' / 'cold scan: complete'. Programmatic consumers (the harness, dashboards, agents) want the same signal via the MCP surface.

Add a 'scans_in_flight' list to the eng_get_status result:

  {
    "status": "ok",
    "schema_version": 9,
    "repo_count": 1,
    "scans_in_flight": [
      {"repo_id": "…", "phase": "walking|promoting|done", "started_at": 1779…, "files_saved": 320}
    ],
    "pending_embeds": 145
  }

Maintain it as a daemon-level in-memory tracker (sync.Map keyed by repo_id), populated when the cold-scan reparser's start log fires and cleared when the complete/failure log fires. Inject the tracker into NewColdScanReparser via a functional option so tests can substitute a fake.

Acceptance: while a cold scan is in flight, eng_get_status surfaces the scanning repo. The tests/mcp harness gains a check that 'scans_in_flight' is empty when no work is happening.

Minor UX gap from Sam's exploratory journey. eng_find_owner against a repo with no CODEOWNERS file returns:

  {"owner": null, "source": null}

A user can't tell whether (a) the repo has no CODEOWNERS, (b) the file isn't covered by any rule, or (c) the tool is broken. All three look identical.

Fix: include a 'reason' field in the response when owner is null, e.g.:

  {"owner": null, "source": null, "reason": "no CODEOWNERS file in repo root"}
  {"owner": null, "source": null, "reason": "file matches no rule"}

Low priority — purely cosmetic. Most repos do have CODEOWNERS.
